herobrine 2023-04-18 10:33 PM
• Caustic was a good starting point for making EDM tracks. It has automation, filters, and basic effects in most DAWs, and I was able to make music on my phone wherever I went. However, all of the tracks were MIDI because recording audio on the app was tedious. The app treats recording as samples that need to be put into a piano roll, and these samples only play when a MIDI note is placed. You can't just drag and drop audio files into the arrangement view. • BandLab fixed that problem for me. I made instrumentals on Caustic and then use BandLab to record vocals and other non-one off audio stuff, all on my phone. BandLab has good effects, especially for vocals, but it doesn't have automation, which I need. • When I got my first laptop in 2022, I immediately installed FL Studio. It's an awesome DAW that almost everyone uses, and I learned a lot from it (how VSTs work, arranging tracks, and mixing although I still struggle with mixing). • FINALLLLYYYYY, I fell in love with Ableton the moment I used it. It looks simple and intuitive, maybe because the GUI is similar to video editing software, which I've been using for a long time. All of the things I learned in FL Studio have transferred smoothly to Ableton, and I've been using it for a couple of months now. Ableton is most definitely my favorite DAW out of all the ones I’ve used.
10:33 PM
Sorry for the middle school type of essay writing, I’m not good with words

Robdeltonie 2023-04-30 1:32 AM
I previously posted this in Owlnest, and Panda told me to post it here instead. So, here it goes: I started dabbling into different AI voice-changing tools, specifically So-VITS-SVC. I did so with one goal in mind: To finally create a version of Owl City's Honey and the Bee that features Taylor Swift instead of Breanne Duren. I don't have anything against Breanne, but considering Adam was likely considering Taylor for the song but it not working out due to scheduling issues, I wanted to re-create what could have been using the powers of AI. Now, I'm nowhere near as good a singer as Taylor Swift, and my singing voice is extremely low that I didn't think it would work well with it. So, I used Emvoice to re-create dry stems of most of Breanne's parts. I then used the aforementioned AI tool to transform the audio from Emvoice into audio that sounds like Taylor, and this was the result. It turned out...okay. I think the main issue is the fact that I'm using a computer-generated voice synth with AI, making Taylor's voice sound robotic in parts. The best solution would be to find someone else (preferably with a range close to Taylor's) that can sing Breanne's parts and run that through the AI. And before anyone asks, "Why didn't you use something like Spleeter to run Breanne's actual performance through the AI?", I did think about it. But between the parts overlapping with Adam's, the vocal processing, and the harmonies, I didn't think I could get a good result that way. Is there anyone here that would be willing to help me with this project? I've included a demo version of what I wound up getting so you can see how it currently sounds. Thanks!
